\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Research Challenge on Prediction of Credit Spread by Machine Learning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Hui Cai, Israel Diego, Yifei Lu, Rick (Yuankang) Xiong, Xinye Xu
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Abstract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Super-resolution microscopy has become essential for the study of nanoscale
 biological processes.
 This type of imaging often requires the use of specialised image analysis
 tools to process a large volume of recorded data and extract quantitative
 information.
 In recent years, our team has built an open-source image analysis framework
 for super-resolution microscopy designed to combine high performance and
 ease of use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Credit spread has been widely used as a symbol for systematic risk, liquidity
 and conditions in financial economics.
 According to the previous literatures, direction and magnitude of the credit
 spread can be explained well by multiple factors including bond characteristics
, credit quality, market conditions and so on (Corporate bond credit spreads
 and forecast dispersion).
 The conclusions of the structural approach regarding the shape of the term
 structure of credit spreads are confirmed by the empirical work of Sarig
 and Warga (1989), Fons (1994), Bohn (1999), and Lando and Mortensen 2005.
 Option-implied volatility is also a measure for future cash flow uncertainty
 (see, e.g., Chiras and Manaster, 1978).
 The market jump risk factor constructed from high frequency data also seems
 to be able to capture the low frequency movements in credit spreads in
 terms of long-run trend.
 (Realized jumps on financial markets and predicting credit spreads).
 To capture changes in the overall economy, we use quarterly S&P 500 index
 returns.
 This paper explores effective features and methodologies using comparable
 machine learning techniques to predict the direction of credit spread.
 Also, it covers some potential shortcomings of each approach.
 (Leverage paper???)
\end_layout

